english:
  title: Letter to Prime Minister Xiao Ju
  author: Choe Chiwon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant has repeatedly submitted memorials requesting that Your Majesty undertake a royal tour, pouring out his loyalty time and again, yet the imperial gaze has not returned. Hoping to preserve his service from beginning to end, he now presents again the advantages and disadvantages of such a journey. Not seeking a hunt at Heyang, he wishes instead for leisure along the Fen Waters.

    Considering the matter carefully: the tax burdens of all provinces follow arduous mountain paths where five must be borrowed to yield but one. Across ten thousand streams and a thousand peaks, the tributes rendered fall short of the costs incurred. How much more so when, in these recent times, calamities appear from the west toward Shu and south toward Jingmen? I fear this portends greater disasters. Should bandit forces suddenly invade and Jiangling be cut off, blockades would multiply and tributes could not reach the court. Or if barbarian tribes spy an opening and must be countered at Yueyue, we would dodge the pillar only to strike the beam. Vigilance against small troubles is indeed wise, yet like one who loses a sword while sailing, such entanglements grow difficult to resolve.

    Your servant, as a filial son does not flatter his father, nor a loyal minister his lord, has presumed to speak these foolish words, offending the imperial ear. He but humbly hopes that the Dragon Boat might drift briefly, that the court might remove to Phoenix Gates, so that the Nine Provinces may perfect their tribute without fail, that each region's proper offerings flow, and the Four Seas return to benevolence. Thus the hopes of all paying court to Heaven may be fulfilled.

    Furthermore, though the rebel rabble, fierce and wild, have long corrupted the realm, even if their nest were overturned swiftly, how could the imperial carriage suddenly return? Huainan lies within the realm, abundant and flourishing beyond the borders—comparable to a golden vessel eternally without flaw, unlike the Jade Mountains in their lesser splendor. Your Excellency stands in a court where intent is focused, holding a position of great influence. When King Cheng of Zhou divined the location of Luo, he entrusted Duke Zhou. When the Jin Emperor crossed the great river, he relied upon his uncle. Declare your decision early and support the imperial will, that eternal glory may be achieved and virtue without self-interest be revealed.

    When your servant was recently in West Sichuan administering affairs and extending peace toward the southern states, though observing small details first, how could he suddenly trumpet his victories? Yet because Your Excellency has witnessed all with your own eyes, he dared not deceive you to your face. Today, as calamities still plague Jingchu and the blessed lands of Wu and Chu are indeed fit for the capital's removal, matters demand flexibility and transformation flows from stillness. Thus may eternal order be established in this realm through boundless sincerity across ten thousand li. Your servant speaks no falsehoods; his intention looks only to foresight. Not seeking position as imperial astrologer, he hopes merely to repay the Son of Heaven's grace. As a foreign sojourner, I pray you judge me not harshly. I respectfully submit this memorial.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Heyang and Fen Waters: The author is politely redirecting the emperor''s proposed route away from Heyang (in present-day Henan) to the Fen River region, suggesting an alternative that would cause less burden to the provinces.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dragon Boat and Phoenix Gates: Poetic references to the imperial court and its movements.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'King Cheng of Zhou and Duke Zhou: References to the founding of the Eastern Zhou capital at Luo, established through the counsel of Duke Zhou, a legendary sage-minister.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jin Emperor crossing the river: An allusion to strategic relocation and wise counsel from trusted advisors during periods of transition.'
